A.  OVERVIEW:

In 1993, there were 190,000 microcomputer units sold in Austria with a total
turnover value of AS (Austrian Schillings) 5 billion (approximately USD 430
million). This represents a 15 percent increase in units, but a 5 percent
decline in value compared to 1992. The rate of decline in value (approximately
5 percent) is considerably lower than a year ago. A trend for more
sophisticated systems was noted. Most of the 386SX/SL models were replaced by
486 DX/SX models by the end of 1993.

Market segments for professional equipment enjoyed higher acceptance in 1993.
Such equipment includes stand-alones for home office use, as well as steadily
increasing terminal use for workstations for mainframes. The number of
suppliers of low-end equipment from the Far East declined in 1993. Possible
quality/service problems of these products, the declining price advantage, and
the trend for label products made such imports less attractive.

The microcomputer is now used for all data processing applications. Among
end-user groups, small firms show the lowest rate of saturation, which should
guarantee a further growth of the market in Austria.

Remarkable growth rates are reported for portables and notebooks. Demand for
lower-priced models and more expensive specialized equipment was relatively
balanced. An annual increase of 30 percent for portables and notebooks is
forecast for 1994 and 1995, while growth for conventional microcomputers is
estimated at 5 percent in 1994. Approximately 35,000 portables were sold in
1993, a 56 percent increase over 1992.


