C.  MARKET ASSESSMENT

The Austrian market for microcomputers increased by 15 percent in volume and
declined by 40.3 percent in value in 1993. Imports of microcomputers declined
17 percent in value and 34 percent in volume in 1993 compared to 1992. The
United States is the main source of imports, followed by Germany. U.S. sales
of microcomputers to Austria declined by 7,289 units or 32.7 percent in value
over 1992. Industry experts forecast a marginal growth of 7.7 percent in value
in 1994 for the entire microcomputer sector and 30 percent for portables and
notebooks. According to the International Exhibition for Business Organization
"IFABO", held in Vienna May 3-7, 1994, innovators in the personal computer
sector remain the market leaders in all lines of the computer business.
Therefore, suppliers of microcomputers, portables, input-output databases with
LAN connectivity, voice recognition, multimedia capabilities and desk-top
publishing have strong opportunities in this market. A trend toward
professional microcomputers with processors comparable to the INTEL 486 was
noted by exhibitors.

Computer suppliers are targeting small and medium-sized enterprises, since
penetration of modern office equipment into these groups is still relatively
low. Approximately 47,500 units were sold to government agencies in 1993 which
accounts for 25 percent of the market.

The average price for a professional microcomputer is USD 2,000; for a
portable: USD 3,000; and for equipment with multimedia capabilities: USD
7,000. Declining costs of computer equipment, and increasing computing and
storage capacities, continue to make the use of computers and peripheral
equipment attractive. An additional factor is the growing acceptance of the
computer as a working tool at all levels of Austria's workforce. Continuing
substantial improvement in the price/performance ratio of new microcomputer
equipment and improved "user friendliness" of such equipment have contributed
to further demand.

The country's economy is dominated by a multitude of small companies, even
though a few large enterprises, mostly public controlled, play a key role in
most industrial sectors. During 1993, the demand for micros by the
government-owned industrial sector increased. However, small companies,
potentially the largest buying sector in the country, were still the most
important purchasers in 1993.

About 200 general agents and importers of microcomputers in Austria supply
approximately 1,200 computer retailers.


