E.  COMPETITIVE SITUATION

In 1993, as in previous years, the United States was the main source of
imports for microcomputer equipment, with a total market share of 24.2 percent
or USD 63 million. This situation is expected to remain unchanged in 1994.
Germany ranks second among suppliers of micros with a market share of 21.4
percent, followed by the U.K. with a market share of 16.1 percent and Taiwan
with a market share of 4.1 percent. An annual real growth rate of 5 percent is
forecast for conventional micros in the next two years. However, sales of
portables and notebooks are expected to grow approximately 30 percent annually
in 1994 and 1995. Greater Vienna, including Lower Austria and Burgenland,
accounts for two thirds of the market.

The Austrian microcomputer import market declined 17 percent in value and 34
percent in volume vis-a-vis 1992. Market leader IBM has reduced its prices and
its direct sales of micros to allow its major dealers to increase their sales
to large accounts.

Apple concentrated its efforts almost exclusively on the Mac with considerable
price deductions which significantly increased its penetration within the
small companies sector and maintained a good presence in universities and
schools, one of Apple's traditionally strong markets.

Compaq gained additional market share with the introduction of PRO LINEA and
CONTURA, which are very price competitive.

Hewlett Packard confirmed its strong presence, mostly as a result of the good
visibility of its PC-peripheral products and the excellent level of support
offered by its dealers.

Another supplier is AST, with its new 486SX-note-book, colored premium EXEC.

Olivetti presented its new portable PC QUADERNO with desktop functions and
MS-DOS tools.

Due to the increasing number of suppliers in this market, competition is
severe in all segments. U.S. manufactured microcomputer equipment is in high
demand. However, design, price, relability, installation and servicing,
availability of product and spare parts, plus unique product features are all
factors which are important in deciding which equipment to choose.

IBM has a market share of approximately 26 percent followed by COMPAQ with 18
percent, Apple with 12 percent and VOBIS with 8 percent.


F.  MARKET ACCESS

Microcomputers are marketed in many different ways in Austria. Large
customers, buying equipment directly from the manufacturer, are served by
manufacturers representatives for additional sales and services of micros.
Some manufacturers operate their own retail shops, while others sell to the
market through appointed resellers.

Home and hobby computers reach the end-user through a multitude of channels,
such as: specialized computer shops found in all large cities; electronic
consumer product dealers; office equipment dealers; department stores; and
mail-order houses.

During 1993, the percentage of indirect sales increased significantly, mostly
due to the efforts of the major vendors to stimulate underdeveloped demand
among potential buyers. Two of the few multi-outlet dealers, the firms
Management Data and Computer City, already hold a good share of the
large-company market. Both expanded into the Western part of Austria, where
the economy is dominated by smaller companies. Software houses, which are the
backbone of the newly established indirect distribution supplies networks,
commercialize their micros in small organizations as part of complete
solutions including high level support for their own industry and/or function
specific software.

The French firm ESCOM operates twelve branch offices in Austria but primarily
offers PCs for the home-user market. The German firm VOBIS offers exclusively
High-Screen Far East clones through several outlets in Vienna.

By the end of 1994, ten to fifteen percent of the computer dealers may
disappear from the market. The reason is that in the 1980's the microcomputer
business was handled by business machines dealers and many smaller software
firms. While micro computers becoming less expensive in recent years, profits
declined leading to rationalization of dealers.

Clones are mostly merchandised through small, newly-established dealers. This
contrasts with the tendency in most other European countries, to market clones
through direct mail order, and with the evolution of indirect distribution
channels in Austria, where low PC sales volumes had previously made it
difficult for small dealers to survive.

Neither trade restrictions nor non-tariff barriers exist for imported micro
computer equipment. There is no customs duty for imports of microcomputers
equipment.


